"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-paris-games-are-just-thebeginning-uswnt-star-jaedyn-shaw\", \"text\": \"Arms stretched out wide, Jaedyn Shaw beamed as she danced to the edge of the pitch, leaping into the arms of her teammates on the U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s national team. A familiar San Diego crowd boomed as the teenager basked in the glory of her first USWNT goal, which came just three days after her debut with the team in October 2023. It was a storybook start to the San Diego Wave star\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s international career, but it also marked a watershed moment in Shaw\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s meteoric rise.\\u00c2  Less than a year after her inaugural USWNT cap and goal, Shaw is heading to her first Olympic Games at just 19 years old. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s long dreamed of representing Team USA on the world stage\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and Shaw enters Paris not merely as a member of new coach Emma Hayes\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s roster, but as the team\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 2024 leading goalscorer.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s going to be so cool to compete for a gold medal \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 it does not even feel real to even say that out loud. It means so much to me, so much to my family, being amulticultural and biracial family,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Shaw, who is the first Vietnamese-American to represent the USWNT.\\u00c2  Following a successful youth career, Shaw\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s rapid rise isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t exactly surprising, but ascending at such a velocity could be dizzying for even the most composed of players. That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s why many around her act as a gravitational force, encouraging her to slow down and take in the moment. Longtime USWNT star and San Diego Wave captain Alex Morgan has been one of those guiding voices, helping Shaw zone in and maintain focus. (Morgan will not be with the USWNT in Paris, failing to make theOlympic rosterfor the first time since 2008.)\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAlex has told me a couple times to enjoy the moment and take it in. And also just work as hard as you can,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Shaw.\\u00c2  Shaw took Morgan\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s advice, making the most of those early national team call-ups to become the first USWNT player to score five goals in her first five starts. On a team that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s notoriously difficult to break into, the historic stretch helped establish her as a near lock for the Olympics\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094in a deep attacking pool no less. Talk to those around Shaw, though, and they say there is still more to come, having yet to hit her seemingly sky-high ceiling.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s open to challenges, she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s very humble, she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hardworking, she wants to be better,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d then-interim USWNT head coach Twila Kilgore said following April\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s SheBelieves Cup semifinal. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd while the world is saying, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Yeah, she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s here and she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s arrived,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 and I agree she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s doing a great job, be patient because there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s more.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Shaw remembers talking with Kilgore a couple of days later about her remarks. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was just basically saying we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re not jumping into anything and this isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t something that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s being forced on me and this isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t a pressure thing, this is more just relax and enjoy the moment because there is more to come. This is, just like she said, scratching the surface \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 There is a new chapter after this.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  Back in this current chapter, Shaw finds herself under the stewardship of Hayes, who is eager to turn a new leaf as she ushers in the team\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s next generation. The 19-year-old is part of a young core\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094including 24-year-old Naomi Girma, 23-year-old Sophia Smith and 22-year-old Trinity Rodman\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094that will be responsible for curating a new identity and charting a path forward for the U.S. following a disappointing Tokyo Olympics and 2023 World Cup. Only eight players remain from the 2020 Summer Games, with nine first-time Olympians heading to Paris.  Tactically, Shaw fits Hayes\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s system well, a flexible player able to command multiple positions as a forward and attacking midfielder. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI like all of the positions, as long as I am high up the field, close to the goal. I have never complained about my position,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Shaw.\\u00c2  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s clear, however, that her most effective and preferred spot on the pitch is the No. 10, with Shaw able to drop into the midfield and add dynamism to the U.S.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s attack. She says she likes to drift centrally too, explaining matter-of-factly that it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s simply because \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cthe goal is in the middle.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Shaw\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s magnetic pull toward the back of the net is welcome, especially considering the USWNT\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s recent scoring woes.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cLooking in the last 10, 11 months, you look at Jaedyn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s goal contributions, her goal involvements for the national team and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been significant,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d said Hayes after announcing the U.S. Olympic roster in June. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe is a player that can play across the front line, extremely creative. Hold-up play is exceptional, no matter who she goes against, she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s so strong to keep players off of her and her ability to make a final pass or be deadly in the final third is something that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s really impressed me.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  To Hayes\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s point, Shaw isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099tjusta goalscorer, her field vision has been praised by many, including formerWave coach Casey Stoney, who called her through ball one of the sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s best. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a skill Shaw says she actually honed growing up playing futsal (a five-a-side game similar to soccer that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s played indoors, typically on a hardcourt).\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cMy futsal team played a little bit of a different formation than the traditional diamond that you would normally play in futsal,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Shaw. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe played a 2\\u00e2\\u0080\\u00932, so it was like a box and I played in the back so I always had to find that open pass or the through pass, but it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s super tight. I built that vision there because it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a lot tighter and you have to see it right on and play it right away.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  Other parts of Shaw\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s game have taken time and exposure to professional environments to develop. After two years in the NWSL and 14 appearances with the USWNT, Shaw has started to invite more responsibility with her growing confidence empowering her \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cto rely on myself and just jump into more of a leadership role.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  In recounting her journey to soccer stardom, Shaw is quick to credit her family, sprinkling in charming anecdotes about their abiding support. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cMy mom is so excited, she is speaking in French already,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Shaw says lovingly, adding that her accent will need polishing ahead of the Summer Games. She also boasts about her 11-year-old brother\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first home run and describes the batting cage her mom built for him in the backyard.  Shaw\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s entire family moved from Dallas to San Diego after she went pro, joining the NWSL\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Wave in 2022 as a 17-year-old. She lives under the same roof as her mom, dad and younger brother, while her older sister lives in downtown San Diego, only a 25-minute drive away. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThey don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t see me as \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098the soccer player\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 they see me as me, Jaedyn Shaw,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cComing home to that helps keep me grounded and in the moment. They are so proud so it just helps me kind of enjoy those little moments and want to do more.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  While she admits that there are some natural growing pains living with her family as she hurdles toward 20, Shaw is ultimately grateful to be able to share the beginning of her professional journey with them, especially her brother. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe sees women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s sports as like this is it, this is the top level. He plays baseball, and he only watches MLB and the NWSL. He plays FIFA with the girls,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Shaw. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what I want for the community and I want to be able to give people that experience.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  Soon Shaw will play on the biggest stage of her young career, and she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll need to call on these formative experiences under the brightest of lights. But like a rocketship shooting into the stratosphere, Shaw and those closest to her are sure to be cautious of burnout. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s telling that at her young age, and amid a successful career to this point, Shaw knows the highest of highs can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be maintained. Inevitably lows will come. That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s why she embraces the calls to submit to the moment, with the future idling in her peripheral vision. Lucky for Shaw, the present moment is a pretty thrilling one. The world will soon get a look at the next era of the USWNT, featuring Shaw as a lethal x-factor. And should all go according to plan, the 2024 Olympics will be the first of many major tournaments for the 19-year-old, as she and her teammates make this iteration of the USWNT their own.\\u00c2  As Shaw says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThis is just the beginning.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Clare Brennan is an associate editor for Sports Illustrated focused on women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s sports. Before joining SI in October 2022, she worked as an associate editor at Just Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Sports and as an associate producer for WDET in Detroit. Brennan has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in international studies from the University of Wisconsin and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in art history from Wayne State University.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"